387
00:44:31,114 --> 00:44:32,157
And that keeps you awake.

388
00:44:32,947 --> 00:44:37,072
And by moving around restlessness, especially if you move, if you go the opposite way.

389
00:44:37,132 --> 00:44:43,920
So for doneness and lethargy, if you go up the body, wherever the attention is, there's always energy, you see.

390
00:44:43,940 --> 00:44:46,565
So if you move up the body, it actually lifts a bit of energy.

391
00:44:47,105 --> 00:44:48,788
Go from the toes up to the top of the head.

392
00:44:49,188 --> 00:44:51,791
If you're feeling restless, go down from the top of the head down to the toes.

393
00:44:52,211 --> 00:44:56,557
So, you know, it has a sort of way of bringing energy with it, attention.

394
00:44:59,581 --> 00:45:00,742
And...

395
00:45:02,224 --> 00:45:02,726
don't move.

396
00:45:03,447 --> 00:45:04,650
That's basically it.

397
00:45:04,670 --> 00:45:07,896
So with dullness and lethargy you move and with lethargy you don't.

398
00:45:08,617 --> 00:45:09,880
It's as simple as that.

399
00:45:09,900 --> 00:45:10,882
Very simple instruction.

400
00:45:11,181 --> 00:45:12,123
And just hang on in there.

401
00:45:12,184 --> 00:45:13,547
Wait for it to sort of give.

402
00:45:15,269 --> 00:45:16,612
And if you don't, fine, okay.

403
00:45:17,094 --> 00:45:17,775
It's going to come back.

404
00:45:17,795 --> 00:45:19,938
You'll have plenty of opportunity to work with this stuff.

405
00:45:20,960 --> 00:45:22,184
It's not as though you failed.

406
00:45:22,244 --> 00:45:25,009
You know, like you say, oh my god, I failed, you know.

407
00:45:27,402 --> 00:45:45,951
and running with that is remorse guilt shame you can sort of put all that in and that makes you very fidgety you know guilt shame and all that and when those things come up yeah you have to sit with it sit with it and if something comes up which you feel you can put right

408
00:45:46,572 --> 00:46:09,610
perhaps something comes in your mind where you've said something sharp to somebody and upset them so you make a decision to as it were you know to close off that karmic line by just apologizing as simple as that whether they accept the apology or not doesn't matter you've actually cleared it within your own heart that's where the what's important

409
00:46:11,074 --> 00:46:13,318
And then finally there's this skeptical doubt.

410
00:46:13,739 --> 00:46:19,309
So that skeptical doubt is the inability to believe anything.

411
00:46:20,610 --> 00:46:23,456
And it's a stopper, it's a killer.

412
00:46:24,157 --> 00:46:29,827
You just won't do anything if you don't have some sort of confidence in it.

413
00:46:29,847 --> 00:46:35,597
And it can be fear or aversion, fear I think mainly.

414
00:46:37,282 --> 00:46:47,711
If you're of a very, you know, I occasionally meet somebody of a very scientific state of mind, frame of mind, and everything has to be measurable, you know.

415
00:46:47,992 --> 00:46:55,940
So even though you, you know, like an alternative medicine like homeopathy, see, they can't understand it.

416
00:46:56,320 --> 00:46:56,581
I know.

417
00:46:58,083 --> 00:46:58,802
They can't understand it.

418
00:46:58,822 --> 00:47:01,266
It doesn't, like, there's nothing in the medicine.

419
00:47:01,585 --> 00:47:04,369
So it's, you know, it's like, it's all hocus-pocus.

420
00:47:04,753 --> 00:47:11,760
And even though you say, well, if it's true medicine, I mean, if it really is true medicine, it'll work whether you believe it or not.

421
00:47:11,900 --> 00:47:12,601
It's like an aspirin.

422
00:47:13,202 --> 00:47:14,563
Whether you believe it or not, it'll work.

423
00:47:15,023 --> 00:47:16,365
So I say, have a go.

424
00:47:16,826 --> 00:47:19,088
No, no, don't go near it.

425
00:47:19,108 --> 00:47:19,989
It's like there's a block.

426
00:47:21,170 --> 00:47:27,657
Just don't go near it.

427
00:47:27,677 --> 00:47:30,940
So there are three things that you obviously can be skeptical of.

428
00:47:30,980 --> 00:47:32,922
It's the actual teaching of the Buddha.

429
00:47:33,306 --> 00:47:39,878
So when we feel skeptical about that, always remember that the Buddha never put it to us as some sort of belief statement.

430
00:47:40,639 --> 00:47:44,166
It was always something for us to investigate, to make our own knowledge.

431
00:47:45,748 --> 00:47:50,177
That's why we have these three levels of knowledge or of understanding.

432
00:47:51,079 --> 00:47:53,543
The understanding we get when we hear something, the understanding

433
00:47:53,994 --> 00:47:57,621
when we think about what we've heard, and it becomes our own intellectual knowledge.

434
00:47:57,641 --> 00:48:02,768
And the third one is this understanding through insight meditation, through insight, through direct understanding.

435
00:48:03,489 --> 00:48:08,898
So he wants, you know, in the Buddha's understanding, that is the process of liberation.

436
00:48:09,659 --> 00:48:10,659
Belief is a stopper.

437
00:48:10,679 --> 00:48:15,807
He just, like, you don't investigate, you just bow to the Buddha-rupa, and that's the end of that.

438
00:48:15,867 --> 00:48:16,869
But he'll still end up with you.

439
00:48:17,190 --> 00:48:21,657
He's not going to do much for your hindrances or insight.

440
00:48:22,835 --> 00:48:26,945
And then there's, well, there's doubt in the teacher, heaven forbid.

441
00:48:27,927 --> 00:48:31,476
I can't imagine it, but there can be.

442
00:48:31,817 --> 00:48:40,657
And it's like it's a healthy thing to always question what the teacher actually is saying, you know.

443
00:48:41,143 --> 00:48:45,869
Again, it's not to be taken as, you know, but one tries it, you see, one tries it.

444
00:48:46,550 --> 00:48:54,880
I remember one of my teachers, the main teacher, he said to me, what meditation did you do before?

445
00:48:54,920 --> 00:48:56,300
And I said, Zen.

446
00:48:56,320 --> 00:48:58,222
He said, well, they don't meditate.

447
00:48:58,242 --> 00:49:00,326
And I said, they don't meditate, Saino.

448
00:49:00,346 --> 00:49:01,027
I said, why is that?

449
00:49:01,646 --> 00:49:04,590
He said, because they keep their eyes open.

450
00:49:04,610 --> 00:49:06,733
And I said, hmm.

451
00:49:06,753 --> 00:49:08,534
I said, well, we keep our ears open.

452
00:49:09,882 --> 00:49:12,264
There's dead silence, you know.

453
00:49:13,306 --> 00:49:15,007
It's like, it's prejudiced, you see.

454
00:49:15,027 --> 00:49:17,592
So, I mean, you don't have to believe what a teacher says to you.

455
00:49:18,833 --> 00:49:20,916
But it's good to try things out.

456
00:49:21,295 --> 00:49:22,657
And if it doesn't work, well, yeah.

457
00:49:23,378 --> 00:49:26,282
If you find that there isn't that connection, that isn't, well, yeah.

458
00:49:27,804 --> 00:49:30,126
But the one I think that's most pernicious is oneself.

459
00:49:30,407 --> 00:49:32,349
One begins to lose confidence in oneself.

460
00:49:33,391 --> 00:49:36,936
Often, when a person's been doing meditation for a long time,

461
00:49:37,016 --> 00:49:41,202
and they don't see much progress, you get this coming up, you know.

462
00:49:41,804 --> 00:49:55,644
But usually they've taken a very short-term view, and when you actually ask them to look back over the years to where they were when they first started, and they, you know, they can normally see it's progress.

463
00:49:55,664 --> 00:49:59,150
Everybody that's happened to them, I've talked to, sees progress.

464
00:49:59,550 --> 00:50:02,534
It's just it's never progressive enough, that's all.

465
00:50:02,554 --> 00:50:04,998
We're not expected to be fully liberated by now.

466
00:50:05,958 --> 00:50:11,387
So, you know, it's like just see what our presumptions are really.

467
00:50:13,251 --> 00:50:19,181
And remember that the path isn't this one direct upward slope, you know, it's up and down, up and down, up and down.

468
00:50:20,824 --> 00:50:27,257
It's just every so often you get to a sort of hill, you can look back and see that the hills that you've actually, are actually lower than where you are.

469
00:50:28,655 --> 00:50:56,518
you haven't gone down so it's a case of when you feel that lack of confidence getting nowhere what's the point all that sort of stuff again just name it you know give it its true name the skeptical death so that's our task anyway that's what we're that's what we're working with on the on the negative side and or everything that we've been talking about of course is what therapy tries to deal with so

470
00:50:56,735 --> 00:51:26,590
in a sense the way we're dealing with this not only brings us this spiritual understanding which are the true liberation it's also helping the heart to purify itself sometimes when you listen to certain teachers actually you get the impression that Vipassana isn't enough

471
00:51:27,295 --> 00:51:28,255
You've got to have therapy.

472
00:51:28,737 --> 00:51:30,320
In fact, I know certain teachers who say that.

473
00:51:31,862 --> 00:51:42,338
And I dare say there are people for whom walking into meditation would be just too much.

474
00:51:43,920 --> 00:51:46,844
But I think the main reason for that is lack of faith.

475
00:51:48,788 --> 00:51:50,309
It's not our culture to be Buddhist.

476
00:51:50,389 --> 00:51:54,956
It's not our culture to have that absolute faith in the teacher like that.

477
00:51:55,914 --> 00:51:59,121
And if you don't, of course, then that undermines everything you do.

478
00:51:59,762 --> 00:52:02,887
I think that's one reason anyway.

479
00:52:02,909 --> 00:52:08,378
In the East, people who are brought up Buddhists, they have just this natural faith.

480
00:52:08,820 --> 00:52:12,507
So when the teacher says, you've got to go through this pain, they go through it.

481
00:52:14,360 --> 00:52:18,925
Not everybody, of course, but I mean, I'm just saying there's that natural sort of faith in things.

482
00:52:21,427 --> 00:52:32,599
And I dare say that there are certain things which Buddhism doesn't tackle really in a particularly, I mean, like madness.

483
00:52:34,101 --> 00:52:39,327
There's not much in Buddhism, at least in Theravada Buddhism, how to deal with madness.

484
00:52:39,347 --> 00:52:41,650
Frankly, that's done by local shamans.

485
00:52:42,793 --> 00:52:51,125
by the local culture, you know, the ancient culture, they're usually better at dealing with that than Buddhist monks anyway.

486
00:52:55,190 --> 00:53:11,349
But for the ordinary person, so the ordinary person with our usual little neuroses and stuff, it's not that therapy won't help, it does, I think some of them are very skillful, but it's not necessary.

487
00:53:13,894 --> 00:53:20,784
And just in my own personal practice, I mean, I never had any therapy.

488
00:53:21,626 --> 00:53:22,847
Childhood traumas came up.

489
00:53:23,849 --> 00:53:26,112
Two childhood traumas cleared out the heart.

490
00:53:26,954 --> 00:53:40,054
And this is exactly what Freud talks about, that these traumas, deeply hidden within the psyche, they're causing all these whirlpools around here, which you're dealing with, not recognizing that there's some deeper disease underneath.

491
00:53:44,606 --> 00:54:12,387
but it wasn't easy that's all it's not easy to really you know squeeze a boil get your thumbs into the side and give it a real till it pops you know what I mean and but what I'm saying is that yes you don't actually need therapy but

492
00:54:13,463 --> 00:54:17,789
A lot of these mod therapies I think are very skillful, very helpful.

493
00:54:17,809 --> 00:54:19,291
And complementary.

494
00:54:19,311 --> 00:54:20,271
Most of them are complementary.

495
00:54:22,574 --> 00:54:23,916
So, that's it.

496
00:54:23,996 --> 00:54:29,003
That's what you're tackling with and it's up to us to just develop our skills.

497
00:54:29,164 --> 00:54:32,389
This is one side of the skills of meditation that we're developing.

498
00:54:39,798 --> 00:54:40,719
So I can only hope.

499
00:54:41,476 --> 00:54:43,498
My words have been of some assistance.

500
00:54:44,400 --> 00:54:59,907
May you, in your wise tackling of the hindrances, overcome them, allow them to dissipate and achieve a full purification of the heart and liberation sooner rather than later.

